04988nam a22007815i 9781400884353DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20162005nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979968835  a97814008843537 a10.1515/97814008843532doi  a(DE-B1597)474402  a(OCoLC)959150180  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHN650.5.Z9M264 2005 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a305.560949531 aGreen, Sarah F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNotes from the Balkans :bLocating Marginality and Ambiguity on the Greek-Albanian Border /cSarah F. Green. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2016] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b12 halftones. 20 tables. 8 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Modern Greek Studies ;v3400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Maps and Figures -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Transliteration, Translation, and Pseudonyms -- tChapter 1. Marginal Margins -- tChapter 2. Travels -- tChapter 3. Moving Mountains -- tChapter 4. The Balkan Fractal -- tChapter 5. Counting -- tChapter 6. Embodied Recounting -- tChapter 7. Developments -- tAppendix. Tables -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMaps and borders notwithstanding, some places are best described as "gaps"--places with repeatedly contested boundaries that are wedged in between other places that have clear boundaries. This book explores an iconic example of this in the contemporary Western imagination: the Balkans. Drawing on richly detailed ethnographic research around the Greek-Albanian border, Sarah Green focuses her groundbreaking analysis on the ambiguities of never quite resolving where or what places are. One consequence for some Greek peoples in this border area is a seeming lack of distinction--but in a distinctly "Balkan" way. In gaps (which are never empty), marginality is, in contrast with conventional understandings, not a matter of difference and separation--it is a lack thereof. Notes from the Balkans represents the first ethnographic approach to exploring "the Balkans" as an ideological concept. Green argues that, rather than representing a tension between "West" and "East," the Balkans makes such oppositions ambiguous. This kind of marginality means that such places and peoples can hardly engage with "multiculturalism." Moreover, the region's ambiguity threatens clear, modernist distinctions. The violence so closely associated with the region can therefore be seen as part of continual attempts to resolve the ambiguities by imposing fixed separations. And every time this fails, the region is once again defined as a place that will continually proliferate such dangerous ambiguity, and could spread it somewhere else.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCultural fusionxEpirus (Greece and Albania). 0aCultural fusionzEpirus (Greece and Albania). 0aGreeksxHistoryx20th centuryxEpirus (Greece and Albania). 0aGreeksxHistoryy20th centuryxEpirus (Greece and Albania). 0aGreekszEpirus (Greece and Albania)xHistoryy20th century. 0aMarginality, SocialxGreecexPōgōni (Region). 0aMarginality, SocialzGreecezPōgōni (Region). 0aMarginality, SocialzGreecezPōgōni (Region). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140088435340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400884353423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400884353.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL